[Scene 1 | 0–4s]
Your neural network is learning NOTHING.
Weights are updating. Loss is dropping.
But the model is basically dead.

[Scene 2 | 4–8s]
The culprit? A bad activation function.
Today we fix that — with ReLU.

[Scene 3 | 8–14s]
Neural networks are just stacked linear equations.
But the real world is NOT linear.
No matter how many layers you add —
they all collapse into one linear transformation.

[Scene 4 | 14–20s]
Activation functions inject non-linearity.
The secret ingredient that lets networks
learn curves, edges, faces, and language.

[Scene 5 | 20–27s]
ReLU stands for Rectified Linear Unit.
The formula is almost insultingly simple:
f of x equals the max of zero and x.
That's it.

[Scene 6 | 27–34s]
If the input is positive — pass it through unchanged.
If it's negative — kill it. Output zero.
Positive: pass. Negative: zero.

[Scene 7 | 34–42s]
On a graph, ReLU looks like a hockey stick.
Everything left of zero is flat — a dead zone.
Everything right is a diagonal with slope one.

[Scene 8 | 42–48s]
That single kink at the origin —
that's what gives the entire network its non-linearity.

[Scene 9 | 48–57s]
The old default was Sigmoid.
It squishes everything between zero and one.
Sounds fine — but it destroys gradients.
During backprop, tiny gradients get multiplied
layer after layer — until they vanish.

[Scene 10 | 57–63s]
ReLU has a gradient of exactly one
for all positive inputs.
No squishing. No vanishing. Early layers actually learn.

[Scene 11 | 63–72s]
ReLU isn't perfect though.
If a neuron's input is always negative —
from bad weight init or a large learning rate —
it always outputs zero. Gradient is zero.
It NEVER updates. This is called a Dead Neuron.

[Scene 12 | 72–78s]
The fix? Leaky ReLU.
Instead of zero for negative inputs,
give them a tiny slope of 0.01.
The neuron stays alive.

[Scene 13 | 78–88s]
ReLU is the default activation
in almost every modern deep learning architecture.
ResNets. VGGs. Transformer feed-forward layers.
Fast to compute. Sparse. Powerful.

[Scene 14 | 88–95s]
Next time you build a hidden layer —
just use ReLU.
And your network will actually learn.